			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65538634"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65538634">The problem with the Dunning-Kruger effect is that it does not work as it is often portrayed. Yes, incompetent people often misjudge their competence (they are incompetent after all), but in general, they don't estimate themselves to be better than the experts. While this can happen, it's more of a statistical fluke than a regular occurrence. To use completely arbitrary numbers to illustrate, the Dunning-Kruger effect describes, how someone with 10% competence would rate himself at 25%, but someone with 90%</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65538634">

</div>
